<div id="review_4396492046" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4396492046" />
    <a title="Mark Reutlinger" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34709487-mark-reutlinger"><img alt="Mark Reutlinger" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1446492966p2/34709487.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4396492046?book_show_action=true">Dec 18, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Reutlinger" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Reutlinger" href="/user/show/34709487-mark-reutlinger">Mark Reutlinger</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4396492046" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer834577277818223545">The premise of ARCTIC MELTDOWN is all too real: a future tug-of-war (and possible shooting war) over the Arctic’s mineral wealth. Geza Tatrallyay paints a picture of diplomatic maneuvering, Machiavellian plotting, and international saber-rattling that could easily represent what is in store for those countries that either hold or covet that wealth, and by extension the entire planet. The story is well-written and displays Tatrallyay’s considerable knowledge of the region and of international pol</span>
  <span id="freeText834577277818223545" style="display:none">The premise of ARCTIC MELTDOWN is all too real: a future tug-of-war (and possible shooting war) over the Arctic’s mineral wealth. Geza Tatrallyay paints a picture of diplomatic maneuvering, Machiavellian plotting, and international saber-rattling that could easily represent what is in store for those countries that either hold or covet that wealth, and by extension the entire planet. The story is well-written and displays Tatrallyay’s considerable knowledge of the region and of international politics, as well as his strong interest in environmental policy. The protagonist is Hanne Kristensen, a Danish geologist who, when she can find time out from her many and varied sexual encounters, attempts to arrange a diplomatic solution that will save the Arctic from exploitation and the world from war. The story will appeal to fans of international thrillers, and especially anyone with an interest in the future of our planet.<br /><br />That said, I believe it might be best to read the book rather than listen to it on audio. Because of the liberal use of statistics, map coordinates, and other somewhat dry (if necessary) passages, as well as an entire international treaty, passages a reader probably would skim but a narrator must deliver verbatim, the story does not lend itself well to audio. Moreover, I did not care for the narrator’s voice quality and reading skills. <br /><br />Read the book. Save the Arctic.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="834577277818223545" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


