    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_724787970" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/724787970" />
    <a title="Norm Hamilton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17052856-norm-hamilton"><img alt="Norm Hamilton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578368603p2/17052856.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/724787970?book_show_action=true">Sep 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Norm Hamilton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Norm Hamilton" href="/user/show/17052856-norm-hamilton">Norm Hamilton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer724787970" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13901672925250217182"><b>A Cerebral Peregrination of Intrigue and Mystery</b><br/><br/>The Arctic is melting. Russia, China, the US and others strive to obtain the rights and control of the resources that lie beneath the surface of the frigid waters.<br/><br/>Hanne Kristensen, a pulchritudinous Danish geologist finds herself contending with corruption and pressure from several avenues. She is shocked by sleazy UN processes and perversions. Antagonistic behaviour from Russian and Chinese leaders coupled with aggressive responses from the U.S. a</span>
  <span id="freeText13901672925250217182" style="display:none"><b>A Cerebral Peregrination of Intrigue and Mystery</b><br /><br />The Arctic is melting. Russia, China, the US and others strive to obtain the rights and control of the resources that lie beneath the surface of the frigid waters.<br /><br />Hanne Kristensen, a pulchritudinous Danish geologist finds herself contending with corruption and pressure from several avenues. She is shocked by sleazy UN processes and perversions. Antagonistic behaviour from Russian and Chinese leaders coupled with aggressive responses from the U.S. and its allies creates international tension and places the world on the edge of major conflict and the Arctic in a precarious environmental position. Greenland and Denmark are hapless in the midst of it all.<br /><br />Contrasting the corporate mandate of political parties is the environmental activists group, the Green Liberation Front. This creates some interesting confrontations.<br /><br />Arctic Meltdown, by Geza Tratrallyay, an extremely well researched discourse on a possible dystopian future the world may be facing. While the tale is clearly written with its bias sympathetic to environmentalists, it is, as the author states, but one of many possibilities.<br /><br />The story is based on actual events, supported by numerous references that are contained in a lengthy section of end notes. (The internal links to the end notes didn’t work in the kindle app I read the book on) Tratallyay provides solid legal, historical and political background to this story.<br /><br />Arctic Meltdown is not your standard thriller full of car chases and shoot-outs. Rather it is a more cerebral journey of intrigue and mystery. The author either has first-hand knowledge of various areas of the world and of political meanderings or has done some remarkable research. His descriptions of places and things are minutely detailed. For me, it sometimes interferes with the flow of the story.<br /><br />While none are overly graphic or offensive, I found some of the sex scenes to be rather gratuitous; almost like they were thrown in for the sake of having some sex scenes. For me, most added nothing to the story. Some were required so we get to know the character better; others just didn’t seem to fit at the time.<br /><br />There are occurrences of narrative being carried by the dialogue thus causing the verbal exchange to become stilted and less believable. Repetitive use of words and phrases as well as some clichés ought to have caught during a solid copy-editing and proofreading. There were also a few formatting issues in the copy I read.<br /><br />This book is not a simple, not have to pay too much attention, kind of read. One must stay cognitive in order to properly enjoy it. <br /><br />If you are interested in a story that will cause you to ponder the world’s situation, both environmentally and politically, Arctic Meltdown is a book you should read.<br /><br /><i>Disclosure of Material Connection: I received a digital copy of this book free from the author. I was not required to write a positive review. The opinions I have expressed are my own. I am disclosing this in accordance with the Federal Trade Commission's 16 CFR, Part 255 : "Guides Concerning the Use of Endorsements and Testimonials in Advertising."</i><br /><br /><b>
  <i>Norm Hamilton</i>
</b> author of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17455482-the-digital-eye " rel="nofollow noopener"> The Digital Eye</a><br /><a href="http://normhamilton.ca/writer/book-review" rel="nofollow noopener">Indie Writer Book Reviews</a><br /><a href="http://normhamilton.ca/writer/services-for-writers" rel="nofollow noopener">Services for Writers</a><br /><a href="http://normhamilton.ca/writer/ " rel="nofollow noopener">Website</a><br />email: <a href="mailto:norm@normhamilton.ca" rel="nofollow noopener">Norm Hamilton</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="13901672925250217182" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
