<div id="review_4249946790" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4249946790" />
    <a title="Keith Steinbaum" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29166053-keith-steinbaum"><img alt="Keith Steinbaum" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586198150p2/29166053.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4249946790?book_show_action=true">Sep 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Keith Steinbaum" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Keith Steinbaum" href="/user/show/29166053-keith-steinbaum">Keith Steinbaum</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4249946790" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13904491340830084487">In author Geza Tatrallyay’s latest novel, Arctic Meltdown, he manages the difficult task of bringing the reader a current events lesson on the international battles between various countries over the vast oil, natural gas, and mineral reserves that permeate the Arctic region while simultaneously entertaining us with a fictional story of environmental heroism and political intrigue.<br/><br/>Due to the highly unfortunate reality of climate change and the melting/disappearing of city-sized glaciers, more sh</span>
  <span id="freeText13904491340830084487" style="display:none">In author Geza Tatrallyay’s latest novel, Arctic Meltdown, he manages the difficult task of bringing the reader a current events lesson on the international battles between various countries over the vast oil, natural gas, and mineral reserves that permeate the Arctic region while simultaneously entertaining us with a fictional story of environmental heroism and political intrigue.<br /><br />Due to the highly unfortunate reality of climate change and the melting/disappearing of city-sized glaciers, more shipping lanes have now been created for countries such as Canada, Russia, China (subsidizing Greenland), and the USA to claim territorial rights to these waters. Tatrallyay does an excellent job of breaking down these conflicts, much of which has been provided by an obviously admirable amount of research. And, as well as this offering, he provides us with a secondary story of both the personal and professional highs and lows of the brains and beauty Danish protagonist, Hanne Kristensen, a memorable character, indeed.<br /><br />I give Arctic Meltdown 4 stars for the ambitious undertaking that Geza Tetrallyay took on and the consequent creative combo fictional and non-fictional elements he incorporated from beginning to end in this educational yet entertaining novel.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13904491340830084487" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

